  year = {2016},
  abstract = {13 A sudden stratospheric warming (SSW) is defined by the World Meteorological Organization 14 (WMO) as zonal-mean zonal wind reversal at 10 hPa and 60\textdegree N, associated with a reversal of the 15 climatological temperature gradient at this elevation. This wind criteria in particular has been applied to 16 reanalysis data and climate model output during the last few decades. In the present study, it is shown 17 that the application of this definition to models can be affected by model mean biases; i.e., more 18 frequent SSW appear to occur in models with a weaker climatological polar vortex. In order to overcome 19 this deficiency, a tendency-based definition, which is not sensitive to the model mean bias, is proposed 20 and applied to the multi-model data sets archived for the Coupled Model Intercomparison Projection 21 phase 5 (CMIP5). In this definition, SSW-like events are defined by sufficiently strong vortex 22 deceleration. This approach removes a linear relationship between the SSW frequency and intensity of 23 climatological polar vortex for both the low-top and high-top CMIP5 models. Instead, the resulting SSW 24 frequency is strongly correlated with wave activity at 100 hPa. The two definitions detect quantitatively 25 different SSW in terms of lower stratospheric wave activity and downward propagation of stratospheric 26 anomalies to the troposphere. However, in both definitions, the high-top models generally exhibit more 27 frequent SSW than the low-top models. Moreover, a hint of more frequent SSW in a warm climate is 28 commonly found. 29 30}
