  issn = {17577799},
  doi = {10.1002/wcc.125},
  abstract = {We review the scientific literature since the 1960s to examine the evolution of\textbackslash r\textbackslash nmodeling tools and observations that have advanced understanding of global\textbackslash r\textbackslash nstratospheric temperature changes. Observations show overall cooling of the\textbackslash r\textbackslash nstratosphere during the period for which they are available (since the late 1950s and\textbackslash r\textbackslash nlate 1970s from radiosondes and satellites, respectively), interrupted by episodes\textbackslash r\textbackslash nof warming associated with volcanic eruptions, and superimposed on variations\textbackslash r\textbackslash nassociated with the solar cycle. There has been little global mean temperature\textbackslash r\textbackslash nchange since about 1995. The temporal and vertical structure of these variations\textbackslash r\textbackslash nare reasonably well explained bymodels that include changes in greenhouse gases,\textbackslash r\textbackslash nozone, volcanic aerosols, and solar output, although there are significant uncertainties\textbackslash r\textbackslash nin the temperature observations and regarding the nature and influence of past\textbackslash r\textbackslash nchanges in stratospheric water vapor. As a companion to a recent WIREs review of\textbackslash r\textbackslash ntropospheric temperature trends, this article identifies areas of commonality and\textbackslash r\textbackslash ncontrast between the tropospheric and stratospheric trend literature. For example,\textbackslash r\textbackslash nthe increased attention over time to radiosonde and satellite data quality has\textbackslash r\textbackslash ncontributed to better characterization of uncertainty in observed trends both in the\textbackslash r\textbackslash ntroposphere and in the lower stratosphere, and has highlighted the relative deficiency\textbackslash r\textbackslash nof attention to observations in the middle and upper stratosphere. In contrast\textbackslash r\textbackslash nto the relatively unchanging expectations of surface and tropospheric warming primarily\textbackslash r\textbackslash ninduced by greenhouse gas increases, stratospheric temperature change\textbackslash r\textbackslash nexpectations have arisen from experiments with a wider variety of model types,\textbackslash r\textbackslash nshowingmore complex trend patterns associated with a greater diversity of forcing\textbackslash r\textbackslash nagents.},
